<br>
<br>
<br>
I have recently cancelled my long running (june 99) account. I have over 250 days played total on that account, as well as some time on 2 other accounts that are also now cancelled. I enjoyed much of my time playing EQ, especially the first 6 months or so. I really believe that EQ was a breakthrough and became one of the most fun games ever. Thanks for a lot of fun.<br>
<br>
Now, for the reasons why I will no longer be supporting EQ in the future. First, customer service. To be honest if the game had been a little less addictive, this alone would have driven me from the game on several occasions. I have never supported a company that had representatives less likely to listen or help in my life. I have had some good results occasionally in dealing with guides but those times are in the minority. My suggestion here is to instruct your people if a decision has to be made, err on the side of the player. I am not saying be a pushover without ever saying no. I am saying when things go wrong in your game: zone crashing, server lag, known game bugs etc. Provide GM rezs, give back quest items, whatever it takes. I have talked to several of your guides who treated me as if I was trying to somehow &quot;rip off&quot; the game. The ill will generated by one such incident is huge. I routinely warn people that EQ is a good game, but the CS is so bad that they should avoid it and other Verant offerings. I myself do not plan to try any of your new games for this reason alone. I have perhaps 15 RL friends who play/played and only one really defends CS to any degree. Of all those friends who played there are 4 left who still play the game regularly. <br>
<br>
Secondly, the game has become seriously unbalanced in melee/caster power since Kunark and it became far worse with Velious. Luclin has not helped. I agree that melee were very underpowered before the expansions. I play a Mage as my main and a warrior at the time could not compare to my pet. It was good to see those players receive some attention. Now the incredible weapons, armor, and disciplines, have turned the situation completely around. This comes from someone who leveled to 50 before Kunark and has been a level 60 epic mage with &quot;UBER&quot; gear for a long time. I cannot compare to the damage output of our guild melee. Feel free to look over my account at any time to check my equipment or time played. In fact, even though we are supposed to be able to solo, I cannot solo as well as paladins in our guild now. This is a class that is not supposed to be able to solo. There are too many suggestions for balancing to list but I have one main idea. 55+ melee with NTOV/Velious Kings gear does far more damage than a same class player with less advanced gear. A 55+ caster with NTOV/Velious Kings gear will have a bit more mana and cast an extra spell. No drop spells that do more damage at less mana cost would be a fair comparision to higer damage/lower delay no drop weapons.<br>
<br>
My third and last point is the time waste involved in the game. I realize that Verant is in business to make money. The longer we stay and play the better for you. Fine, I really don't mind paying to play, and the new alt exp skills if constantly expanded could keep us playing for a long time. The time waste I refer are things like the nexus activation times. Great idea, poor execution. Buses come around every 10 minutes, no reason the nexus can't fire off more often. No binding at the firepots in Timorous Deep? Very few port zones in new expansions, slow boats etc?100+ plat for alchemic gates?  The people playing druids and wizards are not interested in roleplaying taxi drivers. Oh, and one thing that I believe will seriously hurt you in the future is the &quot;Vision&quot;. You make the game and people pay to play in it. Clinging to the &quot;Vision&quot; when the majority of people dislike any part of it is similar to running a restaurant and insisting that patrons eat a certain meal. Sure, it works if you are the only good restaurant in town, but I have noticed several new restaurants lately. Guess we will find out in the next year who is right.Try loosening up a little and you may find yourself building up some goodwill with your customer base.<br>
<br>
As I mentioned at the beginning you have a great game, the entertainment value for the cost is incredible. I really would probably let my account run and play occasionally if I felt that your company was responsive to the issues listed above. However, I believe that as long as everyone keeps paying the monthly fee, things will not be improved at a rate that is reasonable.<br>
<br>
Good Luck, <br>
Osgiliath <br>
